FBIS3-24925 "drafr024_a_94006" FBIS-AFR-94-024 Document Type:Daily Report 4 February 1994 CENTRAL AFRICA Congo Cease-Fire Reportedly Broken in South of Capital AB0302195094 Paris AFP in English 1840 GMT 3 Feb 94 AB0302195094 Paris AFP Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] Brazzaville, Feb 3 (AFP) -- Small arms fire from "armed bandits" in the south of the capital punctured Congo's four-day-old fragile peace here Thursday [3 February], military sources said. The ceasefire agreed Sunday between President Pascal Lissouba's ruling party and the main opposition party of Bernard Kolelas was still holding, military sources added. A fourth railway worker died Wednesday night from his wounds following a machine-gun attack Tuesday as they tried to reopen the key rail route between Brazzaville and the main port Pointe Noire. Politicians said rebel forces had not received word of the ceasefire. The date for reopening the railway was put back to February 8 following the attack.
